<p><b>Kia Motor Corporation</b> (<a href="/wiki/Hangul" title="Hangul">Hangul</a>:&#160;<span lang="ko-Hang" xml:lang="ko-Hang">기아자동차</span>; <a href="/wiki/Hanja" title="Hanja">Hanja</a>:&#160;<span lang="ko-Hani" xml:lang="ko-Hani">起亞自動車</span>, <small>IPA:&#160;</small><span title="Representation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Help:IPA_for_Korean" title="Help:IPA for Korean">[ki.a]</a></span>, literally "Kia automobile"; stylized as <b>KIΛ</b>), headquartered in <a href="/wiki/Seoul" title="Seoul">Seoul</a>, is South Korea's second-largest <a href="/wiki/Automaker" class="mw-redirect" title="Automaker">automobile manufacturer</a>, following the <a href="/wiki/Hyundai_Motor_Company" title="Hyundai Motor Company">Hyundai Motor Company</a>, with sales of over 3.3&#160;million vehicles in 2015. As of December 2015<sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Kia_Motors&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, the Kia Motor Corporation is 33.88% minority owned by the Hyundai Motor Company totaling just over $6 billion USD. Kia Motor Corporation is a minority owner of more than twenty Hyundai subsidiaries ranging from 4.9% up to 45.37% totaling more than $8.3 billion USD.</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Etymology">Etymology</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kia_Motors&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Etymology">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>According to Kia Motors, the name "Kia" derives from the Sino-Korean characters <i>ki</i> (起, "to come out") and <i>a</i> (亞, which stands for <i>(East) Asia</i>), it is roughly translated as "to come out of the east."</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kia_Motors&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: History">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="thumb tleft">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Kia_Motors_South_Korea_factory.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/97/Kia_Motors_South_Korea_factory.jpg/170px-Kia_Motors_South_Korea_factory.jpg" width="170" height="113" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/97/Kia_Motors_South_Korea_factory.jpg/255px-Kia_Motors_South_Korea_factory.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/97/Kia_Motors_South_Korea_factory.jpg/340px-Kia_Motors_South_Korea_factory.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2560" data-file-height="1704" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Kia_Motors_South_Korea_factory.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Kia Motors' South Korean factory</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Kia was founded in December 1944 as Kyungsung Precision Industry, a manufacturer of steel tubing and bicycle parts, eventually producing Korea's first domestic bicycle, the Samchully, in 1951.<sup id="cite_ref-www.kia.com_1-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-www.kia.com-1">[1]</a></sup> In 1952, Kyungsung Precision Industry changed its name to Kia Industries,<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup> and later built <a href="/wiki/Honda" title="Honda">Honda</a>-licensed small motorcycles (starting in 1957), Mazda-licensed trucks (1962) and cars (1974). The company opened its first integrated automotive assembly plant in 1973, the <a href="/wiki/Kia_Design_and_Manufacturing_Facilities#Sohari_Plant" class="mw-redirect" title="Kia Design and Manufacturing Facilities">Sohari Plant</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-edm1_6-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-edm1-6">[6]</a></sup> Kia built the small <a href="/wiki/Kia_Brisa" class="mw-redirect" title="Kia Brisa">Brisa</a> range of cars until 1981, when production came to an end after the new military dictator <a href="/wiki/Chun_Doo-hwan" title="Chun Doo-hwan">Chun Doo-hwan</a> enforced industry consolidation. This forced Kia to give up passenger cars and focus entirely on light trucks.<sup id="cite_ref-Graduate5_7-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Graduate5-7">[7]</a></sup> Prior to the forced 1981 shutdown, Kia rounded out its passenger car lineup with two other foreign models assembled under license: the <a href="/wiki/Fiat_132" title="Fiat 132">Fiat 132</a><sup id="cite_ref-kiamedia.com_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-kiamedia.com-8">[8]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-thehyway.com_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-thehyway.com-9">[9]</a></sup> and the <a href="/wiki/Peugeot_604" title="Peugeot 604">Peugeot 604</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-kianz_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-kianz-10">[10]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-kiaau_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-kiaau-11">[11]</a></sup></p>
<p>Starting in 1986 (when only 26 cars were manufactured, followed by over 95,000 the next year),<sup id="cite_ref-BK89_12-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-BK89-12">[12]</a></sup> Kia rejoined the automobile industry in partnership with <a href="/wiki/Ford_Motor_Company" title="Ford Motor Company">Ford</a>. Kia produced several <a href="/wiki/Mazda" title="Mazda">Mazda</a>-derived vehicles for both domestic sales in South Korea and for export into other countries. These models included the <a href="/wiki/Saipa_141" class="mw-redirect" title="Saipa 141">Kia Pride</a>, based on the <a href="/wiki/Mazda_121" title="Mazda 121">Mazda 121</a>, and the <a href="/wiki/Kia_Avella" class="mw-redirect" title="Kia Avella">Avella</a>, which were sold in North America and <a href="/wiki/Australasia" title="Australasia">Australasia</a> as the <a href="/wiki/Ford_Festiva" title="Ford Festiva">Ford Festiva</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ford_Aspire" title="Ford Aspire">Ford Aspire</a>.</p>
<p>In 1992, Kia Motors America was incorporated in the United States. The first Kia-branded vehicles in the United States were sold from four dealerships in <a href="/wiki/Portland,_Oregon" title="Portland, Oregon">Portland, Oregon</a> in February 1994.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (June 2011)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> Since then, Kia methodically expanded one region at a time. Dealers in 1994 sold the <a href="/wiki/Kia_Sephia" title="Kia Sephia">Sephia</a>; and a few years later, the United States segment expanded their line with the addition of the <a href="/wiki/Kia_Sportage" title="Kia Sportage">Sportage</a>. Over one hundred Kia dealerships existed across thirty states by 1995, selling a record 24,740 automobiles.<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">[13]</a></sup></p>
<p>However, during the <a href="/wiki/Asian_financial_crisis" class="mw-redirect" title="Asian financial crisis">Asian financial crisis</a>, Kia declared bankruptcy in 1997; and in 1998 reached an agreement with <a href="/wiki/Hyundai_Motor_Company" title="Hyundai Motor Company">Hyundai Motor Company</a> to diversify by exchanging ownership between both companies. Hyundai Motor Company acquired 51% of the company, outbidding <a href="/wiki/Ford_Motor_Company" title="Ford Motor Company">Ford Motor Company</a> which had owned an interest in Kia Motors since 1986.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">[14]</a></sup> After subsequent divestments,<sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">[15]</a></sup> Hyundai Motor Company owns about one third of Kia Motor Corporation. While Hyundai Motor Company remains Kia's largest stakeholder, Kia Motor Company also retains ownership in some 22 different Hyundai Motor Company subsidiaries.<sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16">[16]</a></sup></p>
<p>Since 2005, Kia has focused on the European market and has identified design as its "core future growth engine"—leading to the hiring of <a href="/wiki/Peter_Schreyer" title="Peter Schreyer">Peter Schreyer</a> in 2006 as Chief Design Officer<sup id="cite_ref-cdo-ps_17-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cdo-ps-17">[17]</a></sup> and his subsequent creation of a new corporate grille known as the 'Tiger Nose'.<sup id="cite_ref-KiaPR_18-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-KiaPR-18">[18]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">[19]</a></sup></p>
<p>In October 2006, Kia Motors America broke ground for <a href="/wiki/Kia_Design_and_Manufacturing_Facilities#Kia_Motors_Manufacturing_Georgia_.28KMMG.29" class="mw-redirect" title="Kia Design and Manufacturing Facilities">Kia Motors Manufacturing Georgia</a> in <a href="/wiki/West_Point,_Georgia" title="West Point, Georgia">West Point, Georgia</a>, representing a $1&#160;billion USD investment for the company.<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20">[20]</a></sup> Kia Motors Manufacturing Georgia opened in February 2010, after Kia recorded its 15th consecutive year of increased U.S. market share.<sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">[21]</a></sup></p>
<p>In August 2014, the company received international attention when <a href="/wiki/Pope_Francis" title="Pope Francis">Pope Francis</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Catholic_Church" title="Catholic Church">Catholic Church</a> rode in one of their <a href="/wiki/Compact_car" title="Compact car">compact cars</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Kia_Soul" title="Kia Soul">Kia Soul</a>, during a five-day visit to South Korea.<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">[22]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">[23]</a></sup> The Kia Soul drew bigger attention than two other vehicles used by the <a href="/wiki/Pope" title="Pope">Pope</a>, their <a href="/wiki/Kia_Carnival" title="Kia Carnival">Kia Carnival</a> and <a href="/wiki/Hyundai" title="Hyundai">Hyundai</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Hyundai_Santa_Fe" title="Hyundai Santa Fe">Santa Fe</a>, because it appeared in the high-profile welcoming ceremony of his arrival at the Seoul Airport on 14 August.<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">[24]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">[25]</a></sup></p>
<p>In 2016, Kia Motors model reliability was ranked first in the United States by <a href="/wiki/J.D._Power_and_Associates" title="J.D. Power and Associates">J.D. Power and Associates</a>, becoming the first non-luxury automaker since 1989 to top that list.<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">[26]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Affiliations_and_subsidiaries">Affiliations and subsidiaries</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kia_Motors&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Affiliations and subsidiaries">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Further information: <a href="/wiki/List_of_Kia_Motors_automobiles" title="List of Kia Motors automobiles">List of Kia Motors automobiles</a></div>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Hyundai_Motor_Company">Hyundai Motor Company</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kia_Motors&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Hyundai Motor Company">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>As of December 31, 2015<sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Kia_Motors&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup>, the Hyundai Motor Company owns a 33.88% stake in Kia Motors.<sup id="cite_ref-Worldwide.hyundai.com_27-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Worldwide.hyundai.com-27">[27]</a></sup></p>
<p>Likewise, As of December 31, 2015<sup class="plainlinks noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Kia_Motors&amp;action=edit">[update]</a></sup> Kia Motors is owner in 22 different Hyundai companies. Their ownership percentages range from 4.9% up to 45.37%.<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28">[28]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Kia_Motors_Corporation">Kia Motors Corporation</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kia_Motors&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Kia Motors Corporation">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Kia Motors Corporation (KMC), founded in 1944, is South Korea's oldest manufacturer of motor vehicles and is now a subsidiary of the Hyundai-Kia Automotive Group. Over 1.5&#160;million vehicles a year are produced in 13 manufacturing and assembly operations in eight countries, which are then sold and serviced through a network of distributors and dealers covering 172 countries. Kia today has 40,000 full-time employees worldwide and annual revenues of over US$14.6&#160;billion. Kia Motors Corporation's brand slogan is "The Power to Surprise". From August 2009 until December 2012, the company has been led by Hyoung-Keun (Hank) Lee.<sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29">[29]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Kia_Motors_America">Kia Motors America</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kia_Motors&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Kia Motors America">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>

<p>Kia Motors America (KMA) is the American sales, marketing, and distribution arm of Kia Motors Corporation based in Seoul, South Korea. KMA offers a complete line of vehicles through more than 755 dealers throughout the United States. For 2008, KMA recorded its 14th consecutive year of increased U.S. market share.</p>
<p>In November 2009, Kia started production at the first U.S. Kia Motors plant, <a href="/wiki/Kia_Design_and_Manufacturing_Facilities#Kia_Motors_Manufacturing_Georgia_.28KMMG.29" class="mw-redirect" title="Kia Design and Manufacturing Facilities">Kia Motors Manufacturing Georgia</a>, in <a href="/wiki/West_Point,_Georgia" title="West Point, Georgia">West Point</a>. As of December 2011, the facility was building the 2012 Kia Sorento crossover vehicle and the 2012 Kia Optima sedan.</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Kia_Motors_Europe">Kia Motors Europe</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kia_Motors&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Kia Motors Europe">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Kia Motors Europe (KME) is the European sales and marketing division of Kia Motors Corporation (KMC). In 2007, KME moved from its previous location at Hauptstrasse 185, <a href="/wiki/Eschborn" title="Eschborn">Eschborn</a> (near <a href="/wiki/Frankfurt" title="Frankfurt">Frankfurt</a>), to a new purpose-built facility adjacent to the <a href="/wiki/Messe_Frankfurt" title="Messe Frankfurt">Messe</a>, in Frankfurt city centre.</p>
<p>From 1995 to 1999, Kia produced left- and right-hand drive versions of the first generation <a href="/wiki/Kia_Sportage" title="Kia Sportage">Sportage</a> <a href="/wiki/SUV" class="mw-redirect" title="SUV">SUV</a> at the Karmann factory in Osnabrück, Germany. From 1999 until production of the model ceased in 2003, all Sportage production reverted to South Korea.</p>
<p>Kia began exporting cars to Europe in mid-1991, initially selling only the <a href="/wiki/Kia_Pride" title="Kia Pride">Pride</a> mini-car. It initially proved popular with buyers, but sales fell towards the end of the decade, and the end of production was finally announced in May 2000, with its successor — the <a href="/wiki/Kia_Rio" title="Kia Rio">Rio</a> — not going on sale for another year.</p>
<p>By the end of 1991, Kia had sold nearly 1,800 Prides in the United Kingdom. The first full year, 1992, saw that figure double, and, in 1993, it increased again to nearly 5,500 units.</p>
<p>The European range expanded in the spring of 1994 when Kia began importing the larger <a href="/wiki/Kia_Mentor" class="mw-redirect" title="Kia Mentor">Mentor</a>, a range of medium-sized hatchbacks and sedans which were marketed as inexpensive and well-equipped alternatives to the likes of the <a href="/w/index.php?title=(Europe)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="(Europe) (page does not exist)">Ford Escort</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Opel_Astra" title="Opel Astra">Vauxhall/Opel Astra</a>.</p>
<p>A facelift in 1999 saw the Mentor name retained for the saloon (sedan), but the hatchback was renamed <a href="/wiki/Kia_Shuma" class="mw-redirect" title="Kia Shuma">Shuma</a>. These models remained on sale until 2004, when the newer <a href="/wiki/Kia_Cerato" title="Kia Cerato">Cerato</a> was launched and gave Kia one of its first serious competitors against mainstream brands.</p>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Kia_Clarus" class="mw-redirect" title="Kia Clarus">Clarus</a> saloon and <a href="/wiki/Kia_Sedona" class="mw-redirect" title="Kia Sedona">Sedona</a> MPV were also launched onto the UK market during 1999, helping Kia begin its rise in popularity.</p>
<p>The Sportage SUV range, first sold in 1995, has been popular across Europe, but, since 2002, Kia has gained more sales in this market thanks to the launch of the larger <a href="/wiki/Kia_Sorento" title="Kia Sorento">Sorento</a>.</p>
<p>Despite Kia's range increasing from one car as late as 1993 to three cars by the end of 1995, British sales actually decreased in that period, from nearly 5,500 in 1993 to less than 4,000 the following year. In 1998, Kia's future in Britain was thrown into serious doubt when it sold less than 3,000 of its whole range – the worst in any full year on the British market.</p>
<p>Kia did not enter Europe's large family car market until the launch of its <a href="/wiki/Kia_Credos" title="Kia Credos">Credos</a> four-door sedan in 1999. This car was similar in size to the <a href="/wiki/Ford_Mondeo" title="Ford Mondeo">Ford Mondeo</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Opel_Vectra" title="Opel Vectra">Opel/Vauxhall Vectra</a>, but, on its launch, was actually less expensive to buy than the smaller <a href="/wiki/Ford_Focus_(International)" class="mw-redirect" title="Ford Focus (International)">Focus</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Opel_Astra" title="Opel Astra">Astra</a>. It had a spacious interior, large boot, competitive asking price, and high equipment levels, but it had little more appeal to sway buyers away from established European brands like <a href="/wiki/Ford_of_Europe" title="Ford of Europe">Ford of Europe</a>, <a href="/wiki/Vauxhall_Motors" title="Vauxhall Motors">Vauxhall/Opel</a>, <a href="/wiki/Citro%C3%ABn" title="Citroën">Citroën</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Peugeot" title="Peugeot">Peugeot</a>. Its successor, the <a href="/wiki/Kia_Magentis" class="mw-redirect" title="Kia Magentis">Magentis</a>, launched in 2001, was still nowhere near as popular as Kia might have hoped it would be, although with a sub-£14,000 asking price it offered the cheapest V6-engined car in the UK, by which time it was rare enough for a six-cylinder car to be priced at less than £20,000.</p>
<p>Kia entered the <a href="/wiki/Minivan" title="Minivan">MPV</a> market in 1999 with the <a href="/wiki/Kia_Sedona" class="mw-redirect" title="Kia Sedona">Sedona</a>. On its launch, it was the lowest-priced, full-size people carrier on sale in the United Kingdom.</p>
<p>With the range expanded by 1999, sales for that year reached almost 6,400 – more than double the previous year's total. That annual sales figure had almost been matched in 2000 by the end of May, reflecting Kia's growing popularity with British buyers.<sup id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30">[30]</a></sup> By 2009, Kia was firmly established as a popular brand in Britain, when sales broke the 50,000 barrier for the first time and the brand now had a share of more than 2% in the new car market. The Picanto was the most popular single model with nearly 17,000 sales.<sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">[31]</a></sup></p>
<p>In late 2006, Kia opened its first own plant in Europe at <a href="/wiki/%C5%BDilina" title="Žilina">Žilina</a>, <a href="/wiki/Slovakia" title="Slovakia">Slovakia</a>, where it has produced over 2.5 million units of the <a href="/wiki/Kia_Cee%27d" title="Kia Cee'd">Kia Cee'd</a>, <a href="/wiki/Kia_Sportage" title="Kia Sportage">Kia Sportage</a> and <a href="/wiki/Kia_Venga" title="Kia Venga">Kia Venga</a>.</p>
<p>Although the European car market knows significant difficulties, Kia announced increased sales in 2013.<sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">[32]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Kia_Motors_Mexico">Kia Motors Mexico</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kia_Motors&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Kia Motors Mexico">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>The company has built a $1 billion manufacturing plant in the northern Mexican state of <a href="/wiki/Nuevo_Le%C3%B3n" title="Nuevo León">Nuevo León</a>, which produces 300,000 cars a year. Details of the factory, built in the city of <a href="/w/index.php?title=Pesquer%C3%ADa_,NE_of_Monterey(Nuevo_Le%C3%B3n)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Pesquería ,NE of Monterey(Nuevo León) (page does not exist)">Pesquería</a>, were revealed in a joint press conference given by Kia Motors CEO Hyoung-Keun Lee and the <a href="/wiki/President_of_Mexico" title="President of Mexico">President of Mexico</a> <a href="/wiki/Enrique_Pe%C3%B1a_Nieto" title="Enrique Peña Nieto">Enrique Peña Nieto</a> in <a href="/wiki/Mexico_City" title="Mexico City">Mexico City</a> on 28 August 2014. The plant was expected to be completed in the first half of 2016.<sup id="cite_ref-KiaMexico_33-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-KiaMexico-33">[33]</a></sup> This factory is involved in controversies because was built on unevenly purchased land and the construction agreement was made with advantage conditions and out of the local dispositions to Kia.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_34-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-34">[34]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">[35]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Kia_Defense">Kia Defense</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kia_Motors&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Kia Defense">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:K-131.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/K-131.jpg/220px-K-131.jpg" width="220" height="172" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/K-131.jpg/330px-K-131.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/K-131.jpg/440px-K-131.jpg 2x" data-file-width="730" data-file-height="572" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:K-131.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/KM131_Jeep" title="KM131 Jeep">Kia KM420</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Kia Motors has specialized in the production of military vehicles with variants and other transportation equipment and by supplying them as a sole maker of military vehicles designated by the South Korean Government since 1976, when <a href="/w/index.php?title=Kia_Heavy_Industry_Co.,_Ltd&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Kia Heavy Industry Co., Ltd (page does not exist)">Kia Heavy Industry Co., Ltd</a> was established. Kia is currently designing a <a href="/wiki/Kaiser_Jeep_M715" title="Kaiser Jeep M715">Kaiser Jeep M715</a>-type vehicle named the <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/rok/kia.htm">KM450</a> for the <a href="/wiki/South_Korean_Army" class="mw-redirect" title="South Korean Army">South Korean Army</a> on license from the U.S. Government. Kia is also the owner of the former ex-Asia Motors factory at Gwangju.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Facilities">Facilities</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kia_Motors&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Facilities">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote">Main article: <a href="/wiki/List_of_Kia_design_and_manufacturing_facilities" title="List of Kia design and manufacturing facilities">List of Kia design and manufacturing facilities</a></div>
<p>Most of Kia's main plant locations are in South Korea:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/List_of_Kia_design_and_manufacturing_facilities#Hwasong_Plant" title="List of Kia design and manufacturing facilities">Hwaseong Plant</a>, <a href="/wiki/Hwaseong,_Gyeonggi" title="Hwaseong, Gyeonggi">Hwaseong</a> production capacity of 600,000 cars per year.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/List_of_Kia_design_and_manufacturing_facilities#Sohari_Plant" title="List of Kia design and manufacturing facilities">Sohari Plant</a>, <a href="/wiki/Gwangmyeong" title="Gwangmyeong">Gwangmyeong</a> production capacity of 340,000 cars per year</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/List_of_Kia_design_and_manufacturing_facilities#Gwangju_Plant" title="List of Kia design and manufacturing facilities">Gwangju Plant, ex-Asia motors plant</a>, <a href="/wiki/Gwangju" title="Gwangju">Gwangju</a> production capacity of 220,000 cars per year</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/List_of_Kia_design_and_manufacturing_facilities#Seosan_Plant" title="List of Kia design and manufacturing facilities">Seosan Plant</a>, <a href="/wiki/Seosan" title="Seosan">Seosan</a></li>
</ul>
<p>Kia also has facilities in China, Mexico, Slovakia, the United States and Vietnam:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="/wiki/List_of_Kia_design_and_manufacturing_facilities#.C5.BDilina_Plant" title="List of Kia design and manufacturing facilities">Žilina Plant</a>, <a href="/wiki/%C5%BDilina" title="Žilina">Žilina</a>, Slovakia</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/List_of_Kia_design_and_manufacturing_facilities#Yancheng_Plant" title="List of Kia design and manufacturing facilities">Yancheng Plant</a>, Jiangsu, China</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/List_of_Kia_design_and_manufacturing_facilities#Chu_Lai_Plant" title="List of Kia design and manufacturing facilities">Chu Lai Plant</a>, <a href="/wiki/Quang_Nam" class="mw-redirect" title="Quang Nam">Quang Nam</a>, Vietnam</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/List_of_Kia_design_and_manufacturing_facilities#Kia_Motors_Manufacturing_Georgia_.28KMMG.29" title="List of Kia design and manufacturing facilities">West Point Plant, Georgia</a>, U.S.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/List_of_Kia_design_and_manufacturing_facilities#Monterrey_Plant" title="List of Kia design and manufacturing facilities">Monterrey Plant</a>, <a href="/wiki/Pesquer%C3%ADa_(Nuevo_Le%C3%B3n)" title="Pesquería (Nuevo León)">Pesquería (Nuevo León)</a>, Mexico</li>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Design_emphasis">Design emphasis</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kia_Motors&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Design emphasis">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<table class="rquote floatright" role="presentation" style="border-collapse:collapse; border-style:none; float:right; margin:0.5em 0.75em; width:33%;">
<tr style="text-align:left; vertical-align:top;">
<td style="color:#b2b7f2; font-size:3.3em; font-family:'Times New Roman',serif; font-weight:bold; padding:4px 2px 2px; width:0.5em; line-height: 1em;">“</td>
<td style="padding:0 10px;">In the past, the Kia cars were very neutral. When you saw one on the road, you didn't really know if it was Korean or Japanese…I think it's very important that you are able to recognize a Kia at first sight.</td>
<td style="color:#b2b7f2; font-size:3.3em; font-family:'Times New Roman',serif; font-weight:bold; padding:4px 2px 2px; text-align:right; vertical-align:bottom; width:0.5em; line-height: 1em;">”</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class="rquotecite" colspan="3" style="padding-top:10px; font-size:smaller; line-height:1em; text-align:right;"><cite>—&#160;Peter Schreyer<sup id="cite_ref-cbd3_36-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cbd3-36">[36]</a></sup></cite></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>Beginning in 2006 Kia identified design as its "core future growth engine" – leading to the 2006 hiring of <a href="/wiki/Peter_Schreyer" title="Peter Schreyer">Peter Schreyer</a> and to the 2005 hiring Tom Kearns as Chief Design Officer.<sup id="cite_ref-cdo-ps_17-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cdo-ps-17">[17]</a></sup> Schreyer had previously worked at <a href="/wiki/Audi" title="Audi">Audi</a> (designing the <a href="/wiki/Audi_TT" title="Audi TT">Audi TT</a>) and <a href="/wiki/Volkswagen" title="Volkswagen">Volkswagen</a> and had won the <a href="/wiki/German_Design_Award" title="German Design Award">Design Award of the Federal Republic of Germany</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-cbd1_37-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cbd1-37">[37]</a></sup> Kearns had previously worked at Cadillac as Chief Design Officer and was responsible for influencing Cadillac's direction of hard angles and sharp lines within their design.<sup id="cite_ref-38" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-38">[38]</a></sup></p>
<p>Schreyer has since been central to a complete restyling of Kia's lineup,<sup id="cite_ref-busweek_39-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-busweek-39">[39]</a></sup> overseeing design activities at Kia's design centers in Frankfurt, Los Angeles, Tokyo, and the <a href="/wiki/Kia_Design_and_Manufacturing_Facilities#Namyang_Design_Center" class="mw-redirect" title="Kia Design and Manufacturing Facilities">Namyang Design Center</a> in South Korea.<sup id="cite_ref-cdn1_40-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cdn1-40">[40]</a></sup></p>
<p>With the Kee concept vehicle, shown at the Frankfurt Motor Show in 2007,<sup id="cite_ref-Kpress2_41-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kpress2-41">[41]</a></sup> Kia introduced a new corporate grille<sup id="cite_ref-Kpress2_41-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kpress2-41">[41]</a></sup> to create a recognizable 'face' for the brand. Known as the <i>Tiger Nose</i>, Schreyer indicated he wanted "a powerful visual signal, a seal, an identifier. The front of a car needs this recognition, this expression. A car needs a face and I think the new Kia face is strong and distinctive. Visibility is vital and that face should immediately allow you to identify a Kia even from a distance."<sup id="cite_ref-Kpress2_41-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Kpress2-41">[41]</a></sup> Schreyer described how the Kia Tiger Nose came to be as he explained, "I was just working on the car and just thinking about different possibilities, and suddenly I found it."<sup id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42">[42]</a></sup> Commenting on the new signature grille in 2009: "From now on, we'll have it on all our cars".<sup id="cite_ref-Tiger_Nose_43-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Tiger_Nose-43">[43]</a></sup> Kia has since featured the Tiger Nose on all of their vehicles, ranging from the compact Kia Soul, on to the edgy new design of the Kia Optima, and to the larger SUV, the Kia Sorento.</p>
<p>Kia cars have won the <a href="/wiki/International_Car_of_the_Year" title="International Car of the Year">International Car of the Year</a> award every year since 2013.<sup id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">[44]</a></sup></p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Controversies">Controversies</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kia_Motors&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Controversies">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>In late 2012, Kia Motors was forced to admit error in inflating its <a href="/wiki/United_States_Environmental_Protection_Agency" title="United States Environmental Protection Agency">United States Environmental Protection Agency</a> mileage claims and had to reduce its fuel economy claims in the U.S. by about 3 percent across the board and to offer compensation to previous vehicle buyers.<sup id="cite_ref-45" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-45">[45]</a></sup></p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Nuevo_Le.C3.B3n_plant">Nuevo León plant</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Kia_Motors&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Nuevo León plant">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Anuncio_de_inversi%C3%B3n_de_la_Planta_de_Ensamble_de_Veh%C3%ADculos_Kia_Motors._-_14871405557.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/Anuncio_de_inversi%C3%B3n_de_la_Planta_de_Ensamble_de_Veh%C3%ADculos_Kia_Motors._-_14871405557.jpg/220px-Anuncio_de_inversi%C3%B3n_de_la_Planta_de_Ensamble_de_Veh%C3%ADculos_Kia_Motors._-_14871405557.jpg" width="220" height="157" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/Anuncio_de_inversi%C3%B3n_de_la_Planta_de_Ensamble_de_Veh%C3%ADculos_Kia_Motors._-_14871405557.jpg/330px-Anuncio_de_inversi%C3%B3n_de_la_Planta_de_Ensamble_de_Veh%C3%ADculos_Kia_Motors._-_14871405557.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/Anuncio_de_inversi%C3%B3n_de_la_Planta_de_Ensamble_de_Veh%C3%ADculos_Kia_Motors._-_14871405557.jpg/440px-Anuncio_de_inversi%C3%B3n_de_la_Planta_de_Ensamble_de_Veh%C3%ADculos_Kia_Motors._-_14871405557.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2416" data-file-height="1728" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Anuncio_de_inversi%C3%B3n_de_la_Planta_de_Ensamble_de_Veh%C3%ADculos_Kia_Motors._-_14871405557.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>
Announcement of the Kia ensamble plant, Mexico City, 2014.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>From 2014 Kia Motors is involved in controversies in Mexico due to alleged irregularities in the construction of one of its plants in the municipality of <a href="/wiki/Pesquer%C3%ADa_(Nuevo_Le%C3%B3n)" title="Pesquería (Nuevo León)">Pesquería</a>, <a href="/wiki/Nuevo_Le%C3%B3n" title="Nuevo León">Nuevo León</a>. The construction of the plant was done in irregularly purchased landslide, and the agreement between Kia Motors Mexico and the Free and Sovereign State of Nuevo León, then headed by <a href="/wiki/Rodrigo_Medina_de_la_Cruz" title="Rodrigo Medina de la Cruz">Rodrigo Medina de la Cruz</a>, was signed with advantageous conditions to the South Korean company (like tax exemptions for 20 years when the standard are 5) and with tax incentives higher than those allowed by Mexican laws extended to the Mexican providors of Kia.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_34-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-34">[34]</a></sup> A copy of the full agreement was published in Facebook by actual Nuevo León governor, <a href="/wiki/Jaime_Rodr%C3%ADguez_Calder%C3%B3n" title="Jaime Rodríguez Calderón">Jaime Rodríguez Calderón</a>, as a part of a prosecution case to Medina<sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46">[46]</a></sup> and he declared that the signed agreement with his predecessor will be cancelled.<sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47">[47]</a></sup> A new agreement was reached with Rodriguez's administration on June, 2016.<sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48">[48]</a></sup></p>
<p>Derived from the case, former governor Medina de la Cruz and other 30 officials of the former state administration were investigated by an anti-corruption prosecutor for alleged <a href="/wiki/Embezzlement" title="Embezzlement">embezzlement</a>, improper exercise of public functions and damage to Nuevo León State assets.<sup id="cite_ref-:1_49-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:1-49">[49]</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50">[50]</a></sup> Medina was placed in custody for this case in January 26, 2017, among other that he is involved.<sup id="cite_ref-:1_49-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:1-49">[49]</a></sup></p>
